Mutable references (`&mut`) let you modify borrowed data. Key constraint: **only one mutable reference** at a time (no aliasing).

```rust
let mut v = vec![1, 2, 3];
let r1 = &mut v;  // mutable borrow
r1.push(4);
// let r2 = &mut v;  // ERROR: can't have 2 mutable borrows

let r3 = &v;  // OK: immutable borrow after mutable is done
```

This prevents concurrent modification bugs. Use `&mut` when a function needs to modify its input; otherwise prefer immutable references.
